Split the data into a train and a test. I used the same code he gave in class with the set.seed number he gave us.

##set the random number generator so same results can
##be reproduced
set.seed(111)
##choose the observations to be in the training set.
##I am splitting the data set into halves
sample<-sample.int(nrow(Data), floor(.50*nrow(Data)), replace = F)
train<-Data[sample, ] ##training data
test<-Data[-sample, ] ##test data

Create a summary for each column.

Next, I used box plots to examine Outcome against continuous variables. For all predictor variables examined, the median score was higher for those who developed DM compared to those who did not. There are some outliers in each plot with Age having the most outliers for those who did not develop DM. The outliers are those who are older. DM2 is typically developed at an older age, thus this finding is expected.

##side by side boxplots
ggplot(train, aes(x=Outcome, y=Pregnancies))+
geom_boxplot()+
labs(title="Dist of Pregnancies by DM Status")

ggplot(train, aes(x=Outcome, y=Glucose))+
geom_boxplot()+
labs(title="Dist of Glucose by DM Status")

ggplot(train, aes(x=Outcome, y=BloodPressure))+
geom_boxplot()+

ggplot(train, aes(x=Outcome, y=BMI))+

ggplot(train, aes(x=Outcome, y=Age))+

labs(title="Dist of Age by DM Status")

Fitting the logistic regression. Ho: B1 = B2 = B3 = B4 = B5 = B6 = B7 = B8 = 0 Ha: At least one of the coefficients does not equal 0.

Only glucose and BMI are statistically significant within the model. Based on this output, I will fit an additional logistic regression using only those two predictors and compare the two models.

full<-glm(Outcome~Age+Pregnancies+Glucose+BloodPressure+Insulin+DiabetesPedigreeFunction+SkinThickness+BMI, family=binomial, data=train)
summary(full)
